thread.title: Exeter City vs Lincoln City: Match preview with Paul Tisdale

author: David_Byrom
title: Exeter City vs Lincoln City: Match preview with Paul Tisdale
text:
Exeter City vs Lincoln City: Match preview with Paul Tisdale By David_Byrom | Posted: August 17, 2017 0 COMMENTS SHARES Comments (0) 
Paul Tisdale says Lincoln City have to be treated with respect after their exploits last season. 
The Imps made national headlines last season as they reached the quarter-finals of the FA Cup, before being knocked out to Arsenal. 
Whilst that attracted the attention at the highest level, Tisdale says the fact they won the National League also makes them a difficult prospect. 
He said: "Even without the FA Cup exploits of last year, any side that wins the National League must be taken seriously. 
"We've seen over the last 10 years or so that any team coming out of the National League instantly has a degree of competency and strength that they roll over into League Two. 
"So even without looking at Lincoln we should hold the winners of the National League with a high regard of respect because it's a tough, tough league to win or be promoted from and if you keep your side together, which they have, with the same manager, there will be a degree of momentum that follows over. READ MORE: David Wheeler column: Exeter City winger on Swindon Town, Lincoln City, Brexit and his future plans 
"I don't think we can do anything but look at them as a top half of the table team just on their recent history and those feats. 
"I imagine it will be a very tough game, we will of course look at their strengths and weaknesses, as we do every team, and we will try our best to give ourselves the best chance of winning. 
"But I'm under no illusions that it will be a difficult game." 
City go into the game on the back of three solid performances but Tisdale says that will count for nothing against Danny Cowley's side. 
He said: "You take every game in isolation and you have to study the merits of the opposition, which we will do against Lincoln. 
"We must take heart on how well we've acquitted ourselves so far but we can take nothing for granted as well. 
"The line is so fine between failing and succeeding that we have to start in the same manner that we have approached the last three games against Lincoln."
